"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759810","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-09-20","<p>Public protection is our priority. All offenders must meet strict criteria and pass a full-risk assessment before being considered for release on temporary licence (ROTL).</p><p> </p><p>ROTL is used to prepare prisoners for their eventual release from custody and helps with finding work and stable accommodation, and to build and maintain family ties, all of which helps reduce reoffending.</p><p> </p><p>Records indicate that, on 31 December 2015, 80 prisoners were in the community having been released overnight on ROTL. The table below shows the principal offence for which these prisoners were serving a sentence by offence category and, within the “violence against the person” category, by offence.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td colspan="3"><p><strong>Table: Prisoners on overnight temporary release on 31 December 2015, England &amp; Wales</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong> </strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Number</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Percentage of total number released</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Prisoners on overnight temporary release on 31 December 2015</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>80</strong></p></td><td><p><strong><em>100%</em></strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Violence against the person</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>19</strong></p></td><td><p><strong><em>24%</em></strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Murder</p></td><td><p>8</p></td><td><p><em>10%</em></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Attempted murder</p></td><td><p>*</p></td><td><p><em>-</em></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Kidnapping</p></td><td><p>*</p></td><td><p><em>-</em></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Manslaughter</p></td><td><p>*</p></td><td><p><em>-</em></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Causing death or serious injury by dangerous driving</p></td><td><p>*</p></td><td><p><em>-</em></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Causing death by careless driving under influence of drink or drugs</p></td><td><p>*</p></td><td><p><em>-</em></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Assault with intent to cause serious harm</p></td><td><p>4</p></td><td><p><em>5%</em></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Endangering life</p></td><td><p>*</p></td><td><p><em>-</em></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Sexual offences</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>3</strong></p></td><td><p><strong><em>4%</em></strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Robbery</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>6</strong></p></td><td><p><strong><em>8%</em></strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Theft offences</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>6</strong></p></td><td><p><strong><em>8%</em></strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Drug offences</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>35</strong></p></td><td><p><strong><em>44%</em></strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Possession of weapons</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>3</strong></p></td><td><p><strong><em>4%</em></strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Miscellaneous crimes against society</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>3</strong></p></td><td><p><strong><em>4%</em></strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Fraud offences</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>5</strong></p></td><td><p><strong><em>6%</em></strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td colspan="3"><p>An asterisk (*) has been used to suppress values of two or less. This is to prevent the disclosure of individual information. Further disclosure control may be completed where this alone is not sufficient.</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Data sources and quality</strong></p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td colspan="3"><p>The figures in these tables have been drawn from administrative IT systems which, as with any large scale recording system, are subject to possible errors with data entry and processing.</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2017-09-20T14:52:57.153Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759810/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759810/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759810/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-09-12","Prisoners' Release","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many serving prisoners were not in prison accommodation overnight on New Year's Eve 2015; what offences were committed by each such offender; and how many such offences were in which category of violent offences against the person.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","10081"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759811","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-10-09","<p>The information requested is not held centrally and could be obtained only at disproportionate cost.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2017-10-09T08:25:01.963Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759811/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759811/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759811/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-09-12","Prisons: Crimes Against the Person","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how much has been paid to (a) staff and (b) prisoners in compensation following an assault in each financial year from 2009-10.","false","Biography information for Richard Burgon","Leeds East","Richard Burgon","10173"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759812","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-11-02","<p>There have been 6 applications for emergency legal aid from solicitors acting for victims of the Grenfell Tower fire, which are currently under review.</p><p> </p><p>Most advice and assistance will have been provided via Legal Help (another form of legal aid) which is self-granted by solicitors. These matters are only reported to the LAA once they are closed.</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab",,"2017-11-02T17:01:41.98Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759812/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759812/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759812/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-09-12","Grenfell Tower: Fires","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many victims of the Grenfell Tower fire have (a) applied for and (b) been granted legal aid.","false","Biography information for Gloria De Piero","Ashfield","Gloria De Piero","10127"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759813","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-11-27","<p>The Legal Aid Agency (LAA) reviews the availability of advice in housing matters on a regular basis so as to identify any areas where action is required to maintain service provision. Recent analysis has shown a slight downward trend in the number of providers offering these services, but the LAA aims to have at least one Housing provider in each Procurement Area, taking into account the issues of both demand and sustainability. Where any gaps are identified, action - such as undertaking ad hoc ‘expression of interest’ processes - is taken in order to address these. A new tender process for all civil legal aid contracts is due to launch shortly, with services under these contracts beginning in autumn 2018.</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab",,"2017-11-27T15:46:27.097Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759813/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759813/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759813/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-09-12","Legal Aid Scheme: Housing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what recent assessment he has made of the trends in availability of legal aid housing advice; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Gloria De Piero","Ashfield","Gloria De Piero","10128"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759814","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-10-09","<p>The number of Ministry of Justice (MoJ) staff, excluding staff in HM Prison and Probation Services (HMPPS) who have received a pay increase of either above, at or less than 1% between 31/08/2015 – 31/08/2016 is shown in table 1 below. Table 2 provides information for HMPPS staff and table 3 shows information relating to the National Probation Service as at 31/03/2016.</p><table><tbody><tr><td colspan="2"><p><strong>Table 1 - Increase in basic salary between 31/08/2015 and 31/08/2016 for MoJ</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p><strong>Headcount</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Less than 1%</p></td><td><p>734</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>1% increase</p></td><td><p>17,701</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Greater than 1%</p></td><td><p>509</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Excluded</p></td><td><p>3,357</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Total</p></td><td><p>22,301</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td colspan="2"><p><strong>Table 2 - Increase in basic salary of HMPPS staff as at 31/03/2016</strong></p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p><strong>Headcount</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>% of total</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>No increase</p></td><td><p>18,988</p></td><td><p>53</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Less than 1%</p></td><td><p>747</p></td><td><p>2</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>1% increase</p></td><td><p>4,714</p></td><td><p>13</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Greater than 1%</p></td><td><p>11,174</p></td><td><p>31</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Total</p></td><td><p>35,623</p></td><td><p>100</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td colspan="2"><p><strong>Table 3 - Increase in basic salary of National Probation Services (NPS) staff as at 31/03/2016</strong></p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p><strong>Headcount</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>% of total</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>At or above maximum of pay scale (less than 1%)</p></td><td><p>2,063</p></td><td><p>21</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Below maximum (1% increase)</p></td><td><p>7,665</p></td><td><p>79</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Non-Standard or unknown NPS grade</p></td><td><p>13</p></td><td><p>0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Total</p></td><td><p>9,741</p></td><td><p>100</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>To collate a response for the other years requested would exceed the cost limit</p>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee",,"2017-10-09T13:48:38.953Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759814/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759814/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759814/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-09-12","Ministry of Justice: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many of his Department's staff had a pay increase (a) above, (b) at and (c) less than one per cent in each of the last three years for which information is available.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","10110"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759815","Northern Ireland Office","false","2017-09-19","<p>Details of the number, type, compensation levels and cost of exits from Northern Ireland Office are routinely published in the Department’s Annual Report and Accounts.</p>","Norwich North","Chloe Smith",,"2017-09-19T09:04:47.127Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759815/answer","Biography information for Chloe Smith","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759815/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759815/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2017-09-12","Northern Ireland Office: Redundancy Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, how much has been paid to (a) men and (b) women who left his Department under exit schemes since 31 March 2016.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","10154"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759816","Scotland Office","false","2017-09-19","<p>The Scotland Office does not run its own staff exit scheme. Any departures would be under schemes run by the parent employers of staff; who join the office on assignment, loan or secondment from other government bodies, principally the Ministry of Justice and the Scottish Government.</p><p>Due to the small numbers involved, specific details and costs cannot be provided to protect the privacy and identity of individuals concerned.</p>","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell",,"2017-09-19T09:07:30.947Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759816/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759816/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759816/answer",,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2017-09-12","Scotland Office: Redundancy Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, how much has been paid to (a) men and (b) women who left his Department under exit schemes since 31 March 2016.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","10153"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759817","Scotland Office","false","2017-09-19","<p>Scotland Office Ministers regularly meet with representatives of the sector to listen, exchange views and address concerns and will continue to do so to ensure the sector can take full advantage of the new opportunities that Brexit will bring.</p>","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell",,"2017-09-19T13:11:33.303Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759817/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759817/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759817/answer",,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2017-09-12","Free Movement of People: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, pursuant to the Answer of 11 September 2017 to Question 7297, how many representatives of the hospitality sector have raised concerns about the potential negative effect to the sector of restricted freedom of movement after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for David Linden","Glasgow East","David Linden","10237"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759818","Scotland Office","false","2017-09-19","<p>I receive a large number of invitations and travel throughout Scotland to meet with stakeholders to discuss a variety of issues on a regular basis. I am always open to considering invitations from Honourable members.</p>","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell",,"2017-09-19T09:09:28.757Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759818/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759818/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759818/answer",,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2017-09-12","Domestic Visits: Glasgow East","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, pursuant to the Answer of 11 September 2017 to Question 7642, if he or a Minister in his Department plans to attend an official engagement in Glasgow East constituency this year.","false","Biography information for David Linden","Glasgow East","David Linden","10239"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759819","Department for Transport","false","2017-10-09","<p>Registrations of new ultra low emission vehicles represented 1.40% of total new vehicle registrations between July 2016 and June 2017. For cars, the proportion was 1.65% during the same period. In July and August 2017 registrations of new ultra low emission cars are estimated to have exceeded 2% of total new car registrations.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-10-09T13:08:40.97Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759819/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759819/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759819/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-09-12","Motor Vehicles: Sales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what proportion of total vehicle sales were ultra-low emission vehicles in the last 12 months for which there are figures.","false","Biography information for Andrew Selous","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous","10194"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759820","Department for Transport","false","2017-09-19","<p>HS2 Ltd is working with the Department for Transport to agree new governance arrangements relating to redundancy payments including a revised Framework Document which will become public when finalised.</p><p>The senior appointments at HS2 Ltd include a new Interim Finance Director, and a permanent Finance Director who has been appointed and will start in early 2018. Work is underway to appoint a permanent HR Director. In addition, there have been a number of other senior appointments in both teams including Finance Managers, Senior HR Business Managers, a Head of Employee Relations and an Interim Director of Organisational Development. Some of these posts are new roles and some have arisen as a consequence of HS2’s relocation to Birmingham.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2017-09-19T13:49:24.827Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759820/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759820/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759820/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-09-12","High Speed Two: Redundancy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, pursuant to the Answer of 12 September 2017 to Question 7698, on High Speed Two: Redundancy, whether he has plans to publish the (a) new governance arrangements and (b) senior appointments.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","10187"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759821","Department for Transport","false","2017-09-20","<p>Details of the number, type, compensation levels and cost of exits from the Department for Transport are routinely published in the Department’s Annual Report and Accounts.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2017-09-20T14:14:39.99Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759821/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759821/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759821/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-09-12","Department for Transport: Redundancy Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how much has been paid to (a) men and (b) women who left his Department under exit schemes since 31 March 2016.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","10152"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759822","Department for Transport","false","2017-10-09","<p>Network Rail has been considering carefully the risks associated with the proposed transfer of ownership of the Valley Lines. Both it and the Welsh Government have been developing an agreement based upon Network Rail being held harmless for the direct impacts upon its business of the proposed transfer.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2017-10-09T12:33:55.65Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759822/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759822/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759822/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-09-12","Valley Lines","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what assessment has been made of the costs associated with the transfer of risk related to the proposed transfer of ownership of the Valley Lines to the Welsh Government.","false","Biography information for Jo Stevens","Cardiff Central","Jo Stevens","10140"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759823","Department for Transport","false","2017-10-09","<p>As part of developing an agreement for the proposed transfer of the Valley Lines, Network Rail has given the Welsh Government access to information, staff and infrastructure to allow it to understand the current condition of the network and current and future risks associated with it. Dealing with this issue will form part of the final agreement for transfer.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2017-10-09T12:51:41.677Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759823/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759823/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759823/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-09-12","Valley Lines","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what assessment has been made of the current condition of the Valleys network including latent defect; and whether this assessment has been shared with the Welsh Government.","false","Biography information for Jo Stevens","Cardiff Central","Jo Stevens","10141"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759824","Department for Transport","false","2017-10-09","<p>The government, the Welsh Government and Network Rail have been working to develop an asset transfer agreement that represents a fair settlement to all parties for the proposed transfer. Agreement has been reached on the key principles and will be subject to detailed agreement in due course.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2017-10-09T12:57:36.21Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759824/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759824/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759824/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-09-12","Valley Lines","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what assessment has been made of the effect of the proposed transfer of the Valley Lines to the Welsh Government on (a) funding, (b) debt and (c) liability for the Valley Lines.","false","Biography information for Jo Stevens","Cardiff Central","Jo Stevens","10142"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759825","Department for Transport","false","2017-10-09","<p>Agreement has been reached on the key principles relating to the proposed transfer of the Valley Lines. The principle that the Welsh Government and Network Rail have worked to is that Network Rail’s business should be held harmless as a result of the transfer and that Network Rail will not retain liabilities for assets that it no longer owns. Subject to this principle, discussions on the details of future agreements, including on the specifics of future liabilities, are ongoing.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2017-10-09T12:59:20.277Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759825/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759825/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759825/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-09-12","Valley Lines","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what assessment has been made of the future liabilities of the proposed transfer of the Valley Lines to the Welsh Government for (a) the UK Government, (b) Network Rail and (c) the Welsh Government.","false","Biography information for Jo Stevens","Cardiff Central","Jo Stevens","10143"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759826","Department for Transport","false","2017-10-09","<p>Network Rail’s debt will not transfer to the Welsh Government as a result of any transfer.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2017-10-09T13:02:54.523Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759826/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759826/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759826/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-09-12","Valley Lines","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether Network Rail's debt will transfer as a result of any transfer of the Valley Lines to the Welsh Government; and how much any such debt amounts to.","false","Biography information for Jo Stevens","Cardiff Central","Jo Stevens","10144"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759827","Department for Transport","false","2017-09-18","<p>The provision of a temporary bridge is not considered to be feasible on the A63, especially in a location likely to be used by pedestrians, cyclists and disabled users, due to land constraints. It also clashes with the location of the permanent Princes Quay Bridge.</p><p> </p><p>In the short term we will work closely with Hull County Council, to increase awareness of the alternative Humber Dock Street pedestrian crossing by providing additional signage and information.</p><p> </p><p>In the medium term Highways England are investigating whether construction of the Princes Quay Bridge could begin in advance of the main A63 Castle Street improvement scheme works currently programmed for Spring 2020. In order to deliver this element early, Highways England would need the support of key stakeholders including Hull County Council in securing the land to construct the bridge and co-ordinating traffic management.</p><p> </p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-09-18T08:49:19.293Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759827/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759827/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759827/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-09-12","Bridges: Kingston upon Hull West and Hessle","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether he plans to provide a temporary bridge over Castle Street in Hull West and Hessle constituency; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Emma Hardy","Kingston upon Hull West and Hessle","Emma Hardy","10096"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759828","Department for Transport","false","2017-09-20","<p>We want our future relationship with the EU to be based on mutual economic and security interests.</p><p> </p><p>To which end, it will be in the interests of all parties to maintain closely integrated aviation markets. The opening up of access to air services helps to deliver connectivity, choice and value for money that benefits consumers and businesses both here and abroad.</p><p> </p><p>The Government continues to work closely with the aviation sector to ensure this industry continues to be a major success story for the British economy. As well as seeking suitable aviation arrangements with the EU, the Department for Transport is also working closely with the aviation community to ensure that this global industry continues to be a major success.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2017-09-20T15:06:27.017Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759828/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759828/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759828/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-09-12","Aviation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what contingency plans the Government plans to adopt in the event that no replacement for the single aviation market and open skies agreement is available when the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","10160"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759829","Department for Transport","false","2017-10-09","<p>The Department’s Buses and Taxi's division has 27 officials who work full-time or part-time on bus policies. The team does not employ any private contractors. Other officials elsewhere in the Department also spend some of their time working on analytical, policy, communications and other issues that are related to bus policies.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-10-09T12:36:10.777Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759829/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759829/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759829/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-09-12","Bus Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many (a) officials, (b) other staff and (c) contracted workers in his Department are working on buses policy.","false","Biography information for Andy McDonald","Middlesbrough","Andy McDonald","10123"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759830","Department for Transport","false","2017-10-09","<p>It will be in everyone's interest for air connections between the UK and EU to continue. The Government wants to negotiate the best possible relationship between the UK and EU, and is ready to begin discussions on aviation. The Government is well prepared to ensure suitable arrangements are put in place to ensure a smooth and orderly exit.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2017-10-09T13:05:38.86Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759830/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759830/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759830/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-09-12","Aviation: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what steps his Department is taking to avoid disruption to arrangements for air travel between the UK and European destinations when the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","10126"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759831","Department for Transport","false","2017-10-09","<p>We are encouraging the railway industry to improve air quality by proposing solutions that reduce emissions from trains and also to develop innovative solutions around future fuel technologies such as hydrogen and battery power. In the nearer term, there are currently a number of new bi-mode trains being delivered or on order. The rail industry expects rolling stock to typically have an expected life in the range of 30 to 35 years. There is no policy at present on the use of diesel trains post 2040.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2017-10-09T13:06:47.4Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759831/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759831/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759831/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-09-12","Trains: Diesel Fuel","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, with reference to the announcement of 26 July 2017 on the end of sales of all new conventional petrol and diesel cars and vans by 2040, what his policy is on the use of diesel trains after that date.","false","Biography information for Andy McDonald","Middlesbrough","Andy McDonald","10168"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759832","Department for Transport","false","2017-09-20","<p>The Department has three officials working on taxi and private hire vehicle policy within the Buses and Taxis Division, of which one works solely on this policy area and it forms a core part of the work load of the other two. An official will shortly join the Department on secondment to work on policy development. There are no contracted workers.</p><p> </p><p>There are a number of other officials elsewhere in the Department who contribute to work on related policy issues including analysts, economists and statisticians, this figure is not centrally recorded.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2017-09-20T14:04:08.363Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759832/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759832/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759832/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-09-12","Taxis","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many (a) officials, (b) other staff and (c) private contractors in his Department are responsible for Government policy on taxi and private hire vehicles.","false","Biography information for Andy McDonald","Middlesbrough","Andy McDonald","10037"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759833","Department for Transport","false","2017-09-20","<p>The Department’s Active and Accessible Travel team includes approximately 15 officials and 4 secondees from local authorities and other organisations who work full-time or part-time on cycling and walking policies. The team does not employ any private contractors. Around a dozen or so other officials elsewhere in the Department also work in a full-time or part-time capacity on matters relevant to cycling.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-09-20T14:06:54.093Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759833/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759833/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759833/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-09-12","Cycling","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many (a) officials, (b) other staff and (c) private contractors in his Department are responsible for Government policy on cycling.","false","Biography information for Andy McDonald","Middlesbrough","Andy McDonald","10038"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759834","Department for Transport","false","2017-10-09","<p>The Department has received a number of representations from MPs, Councillors, members of the public and the business community in the West End of London about the need to control pedicabs in central London. We have concluded that there is a need to regulate pedicabs and are investigating a suitable legislative slot to do this.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-10-09T10:57:52.61Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759834/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759834/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759834/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-09-12","Pedicabs: Greater London","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what assessment he has made of the need for legislation to control pedicab traffic in central London.","false","Biography information for Ms Karen Buck","Westminster North","Ms Karen Buck","10067"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759835","Department for Transport","false","2017-09-19","<p>The 2015 Spending Review set a funding envelope for Phase Two of £28.55bn (in 2015 prices). Following the transfer of scope of Crewe Tunnel between phases, £3.48bn has been allocated to Phase 2a and £25.07bn to Phase 2b (including provision for rolling stock). HS2 Ltd is expected to manage all elements of the delivery of Phase 2b from within the overall funding provision. As such, there is no separately designated Rolling Stock budget within the Phase 2b allocation.</p><p> </p><p>The amount of contingency available in these allocations has been calculated in line with HM Treasury’s Green Book guidance. Further detail can be found in the Phase Two financial case:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/629165/high-speed-two-phase-two-financial-case.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/629165/high-speed-two-phase-two-financial-case.pdf</a></p><p> </p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2017-09-19T13:53:53.987Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759835/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759835/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759835/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-09-12","High Speed 2 Railway Line","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how much and what proportion of the funding available for the second phase of High Speed 2 has been allocated to (a) contingency and (b) rolling stock.","false","Biography information for Antoinette Sandbach","Eddisbury","Antoinette Sandbach","10283"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759836","Department for Transport","false","2017-09-19","<p>As of the week ending 8-9-17, approximately 217 environmental surveys had been recorded in and around the Eddisbury area.</p><p> </p><p>To date, HS2 Ltd has recorded a total of 90 land access licences as having been agreed entirely or partially within Eddisbury. The corresponding number for those entirely within Eddisbury is 52.</p><p> </p><p>These figures are subject to change.</p><p> </p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2017-09-19T14:02:30.58Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759836/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759836/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759836/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-09-12","High Speed 2 Railway Line: Eddisbury","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many environmental surveys have been conducted on the proposed route of the second phase of High Speed 2 through Eddisbury; and how many land access agreements have been signed between HS2 Ltd and property owners in Eddisbury.","false","Biography information for Antoinette Sandbach","Eddisbury","Antoinette Sandbach","10295"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759837","Wales Office","false","2017-09-19","<p>I hold regular discussions with the Secretary of State for Transport to discuss Wales’ rail infrastructure. From this Autumn, passengers travelling on the Great Western Main Line to and from Swansea will benefit from new, innovative bi-mode Intercity Express trains, experience faster journeys, with each train having an additional capacity of 130 seats. This will improve the travel experience of commuters and passengers and boost businesses in Swansea and South Wales.</p>","Vale of Glamorgan","Alun Cairns",,"2017-09-19T09:12:03.95Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759837/answer","Biography information for Alun Cairns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759837/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759837/answer",,,,,"28","Wales","Wales","2017-09-12","South Wales Railway Line: Electrification","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Wales, what recent discussions he has had with the Secretary of State for Transport on the electrification of the Cardiff-Swansea railway line.","false","Biography information for Chris Elmore","Ogmore","Chris Elmore","10023"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759838","Wales Office","false","2017-09-19","<p>The Government recognises the challenges and opportunities facing businesses across the UK, including in the red meat sector in Wales, and we’re committed to getting a deal that works for all parts of the UK.</p><p>We do not seek membership of the Single Market after we leave the EU, but a bold and ambitious Free Trade Agreement as part of a new, deep and special partnership. We start from a unique position with regulatory frameworks and standards that match. We want to have the greatest possible tariff- and barrier-free trade with our European neighbours, as well as to negotiate our own trade agreements around the world. We want to ensure that UK companies have the maximum freedom to trade with and operate within European markets – and to let European businesses do the same in the UK.</p><p>Last month we published <em>Future customs arrangements: a future partnership paper</em>, which sets out very clearly the Government’s objectives for a new customs arrangement with the EU, and our proposals to achieve them. As we leave the Customs Union, the Government will seek a new and ambitious customs arrangement with the EU that facilitates as frictionless trade as possible in goods between the UK and EU and allows us to forge new trade relationships with our partners in Europe and around the world.</p>","Vale of Glamorgan","Alun Cairns",,"2017-09-19T09:13:18.107Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759838/answer","Biography information for Alun Cairns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759838/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759838/answer",,,,,"28","Wales","Wales","2017-09-12","Meat: Wales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Wales, what assessment his Department has made of the effect on the Welsh red meat sector of the UK leaving the European (a) single market and (b) customs union.","false","Biography information for Ben Lake","Ceredigion","Ben Lake","10177"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759839","Wales Office","false","2017-09-18","<p>No staff working at the Wales Office have left under exit schemes since 31 March 2016.</p>","Aberconwy","Guto Bebb",,"2017-09-18T16:09:55.963Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759839/answer","Biography information for Guto Bebb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759839/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759839/answer",,,,,"28","Wales","Wales","2017-09-12","Wales Office: Redundancy Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Wales, how much has been paid to (a) men and (b) women who left his Department under exit schemes since 31 March 2016.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","10151"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759840","Wales Office","false","2017-09-19","<p>The Government recognises the challenges and opportunities facing businesses across the UK, including in the food processing sector in Wales, and we’re committed to getting a deal that works for all parts of the UK.</p><p>We do not seek membership of the Single Market after we leave the EU, but a bold and ambitious Free Trade Agreement as part of a new, deep and special partnership. We start from a unique position with regulatory frameworks and standards that match. We want to have the greatest possible tariff- and barrier-free trade with our European neighbours, as well as to negotiate our own trade agreements around the world. We want to ensure that UK companies have the maximum freedom to trade with and operate within European markets – and to let European businesses do the same in the UK.</p><p>Last month we published <em>Future customs arrangements: a future partnership paper</em>, which sets out very clearly the Government’s objectives for a new customs arrangement with the EU, and our proposals to achieve them. As we leave the Customs Union, the Government will seek a new and ambitious customs arrangement with the EU that facilitates as frictionless trade as possible in goods between the UK and EU and allows us to forge new trade relationships with our partners in Europe and around the world.</p><p>We will always welcome those with the skills, the drive and the expertise to make our nation better still. We will be setting out initial proposals for a new immigration system later in the autumn.</p>","Vale of Glamorgan","Alun Cairns",,"2017-09-19T09:14:20.053Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759840/answer","Biography information for Alun Cairns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759840/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759840/answer",,,,,"28","Wales","Wales","2017-09-12","Food: Wales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Wales, what assessment his Department has made of the effect on the Welsh food processing sector of access to labour of the UK leaving the European (a) single market and (b) customs union.","false","Biography information for Ben Lake","Ceredigion","Ben Lake","10179"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759841","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-14","<p>There are no current plans to meet with representatives of the Women Against State Pension Inequality campaign in the immediate future.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>This matter has been comprehensively debated on many occasions in Parliament, most recently in a Westminster Hall Debate on 5th July 2017 in which I stated I will be meeting the All Party Parliamentary Group (APPG) when it is reformed.</p>","Hexham","Guy Opperman",,"2017-09-14T14:03:38.647Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759841/answer","Biography information for Guy Opperman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759841/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759841/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-12","State Retirement Pensions: Females","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, if he will meet the hon. Member for Kingston upon Hull West and Hessle and a delegation from WASPI Hull to discuss changes to the state pension age for women born in the 1950s.","false","Biography information for Emma Hardy","Kingston upon Hull West and Hessle","Emma Hardy","10098"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759842","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-18","<p>The publication “Improving lives: helping workless families: analysis and research pack” presents analysis on worklessness, other associated disadvantages and how they impact on children’s outcomes. The publication includes analysis of nine indicators and the most interesting and useful breakdowns.</p><p> </p><p>It is not possible to produce the majority of the breakdowns requested because of the different data sources, definitions and availability of data.</p><p> </p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2017-09-18T13:48:46.053Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759842/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759842/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759842/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-12","Families: Disadvantaged","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, with reference to his Department's publication entitled Improving lives: helping workless families analysis and research pack, published in April 2017, what proportion of families experiencing each Children and Young People's Outcome Indicator from 2 to 9 were included in the (a) workless family, (b) working family in the bottom 40 per cent of the income distribution and (c) working family in the top 60 per cent of the income distribution category.","false","Biography information for Lyn Brown","West Ham","Lyn Brown","10204"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759843","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-18","<p>The “Improving lives: helping workless families analysis and research pack”, compares workless families to working families from the bottom 40 per cent of the income distribution, because this represents a more useful comparison than comparing to all working families.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2017-09-18T13:51:19.66Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759843/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759843/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759843/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-12","Families: Disadvantaged","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, with reference to his Department's publication entitled Improving lives: helping workless families analysis and research pack, published in April 2017, for what reason workless families are compared to families with work from the bottom 40 per cent of the income distribution in that publication.","false","Biography information for Lyn Brown","West Ham","Lyn Brown","10205"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759844","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-20","<p>I refer the Honourable Member to my reply to Question <a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-questions-answers/?page=1&amp;max=20&amp;questiontype=AllQuestions&amp;house=commons%2clords&amp;uin=7645" target="_blank">7645</a> on 11 September 2017.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-09-20T09:40:47.163Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759844/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759844/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759844/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-12","Jobcentres: Glasgow","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, pursuant to the Answer of 11 September 2017 to Question 7645, if he will make it his policy that no compulsory redundancies will occur at any point in time as a result of the planned closure of Parkhead Jobcentre.","false","Biography information for David Linden","Glasgow East","David Linden","10238"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759845","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-20","<p>I refer the Honourable Member to my reply to Question <a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-questions-answers/?page=1&amp;max=20&amp;questiontype=AllQuestions&amp;house=commons%2clords&amp;uin=7646" target="_blank">7646</a> on 11 September 2017.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-09-20T09:41:42.307Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759845/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759845/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759845/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-12","Jobcentres: Glasgow","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, pursuant to the Answer of 11 September 2017 to Question 7646, if he will make it his policy that no compulsory redundancies will occur at any point in time as a result of the planned closure of the Easterhouse Jobcentre.","false","Biography information for David Linden","Glasgow East","David Linden","10240"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759846","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-18","<p>Reform to housing benefit is a central part of this Government’s plan to create a welfare system that supports the most vulnerable and is fair to taxpayers. In order to limit HB expenditure in the private rent sector, Local Housing Allowance (LHA) rates were frozen for 4 years from April 2016. This means rates are either frozen at April 2015 levels or are set at the 30th percentile of local rents if lower. In line with the ‘freeze’ to LHA rates, the LHA national caps (which no individual rate can exceed) are also frozen at April 2015 levels.</p><p> </p><p>Local authorities have strong and effective powers under the Housing Act 2004 to deal with poor quality and unsafe accommodation in the private rented sector, including mandatory/additional licensing of Houses in Multiple Occupation (HMOs), selective licensing of other privately rented properties and the Housing Health and Safety Rating System (HHSRS) to assess the health and safety risks in all residential properties. We have further strengthened these measures through the Housing and Planning Act 2016, introducing civil penalties of up to £30,000 and Rent Repayment Orders for a wider range of offences.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2017-09-18T13:28:13.013Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759846/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759846/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759846/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-12","Housing Benefit: Private Rented Housing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, pursuant to the Answer of 11 September 2017 to Question 8560, what steps the Government is taking to reduce (a) the total sum of housing benefit being paid to private landlords and (b) the total sum of housing benefit being paid to private landlords providing unsafe and unsuitable accommodation.","false","Biography information for Mr David Lammy","Tottenham","Mr David Lammy","10250"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759847","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-20","<p>The Department has no plans to introduce a policy of collecting data on the number of claimants using food bank signposting services.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-09-20T09:35:29.117Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759847/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759847/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759847/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-12","Jobcentres: Glasgow","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, pursuant to the Answer of 11 September 2017 to Question 8086, if he will make it his policy to collect data on the number of people using the food bank signposting services at (a) Easterhouse, (b) Parkhead and (c) Shettleston jobcentres.","false","Biography information for David Linden","Glasgow East","David Linden","10242"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759848","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-14","<p>DWP recognises the difficulties multi employer schemes such as the Plumbers have with the current Employer Debt legislation. The recent Green Paper “Security and Sustainability in Defined Benefit pension schemes” explores these issues and during the consultation period officials have engaged with a range of stakeholders to explore potential legislative changes which could help multi employer schemes. We plan to respond on this issue in a White Paper later this winter.</p>","Hexham","Guy Opperman",,"2017-09-14T14:02:04.507Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759848/answer","Biography information for Guy Opperman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759848/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759848/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-12","Occupational Pensions: Plumbing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what steps his Department is taking to prevent financial disbenefit for plumbers affected by section 75 of the Pensions Act 1995; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Kirstene Hair","Angus","Kirstene Hair","10024"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759849","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-18","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the answer I gave on 5 September 2017 to Question UIN 6544</p><p><a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Commons/2017-07-20/6544/" target="_blank">http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Commons/2017-07-20/6544/</a></p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2017-09-18T13:52:56.54Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759849/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759849/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/759849/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-12","Employment and Support Allowance: Parkinson's Disease","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many people with Parkinson's disease have been placed in the (a) support group and (b) work-related activity group with a prognosis statement (i) of three months, (ii) of six months, (iii) of 12 months, (iv) of 18 months, (v) of two years and (vi) in the longer term since the introduction of employment and support allowance in 2008; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mrs Madeleine Moon","Bridgend","Mrs Madeleine Moon","10093"
